The Nyquist plots, which exhibit a peak at an intermediate frequency, relate to the Bode plots in Fig. 6 . This implies that the double-charged layer at the mild steel-solution interface is solely associated with a one-time constant. Furthermore, Fig. 6 illustrates that at low frequencies, the relative impedance values rise with DHRE concentration. This shows that numerous DHRE molecules may be adsorbed on the surface of mild steel; the more prevalent the inhibitor concentration and the more complex the charge transport mechanism due to the thicker the adsorption layer. A double-layer capacitance (C
dl
) is enhanced by employing a constant phase element since the DHRE component's adsorption properties significantly impact the charge transfer process, allowing for more precise experimental data acquisition. The n values range between 0.5 and 1, indicating that the CPE behaves like an ideal double-layer capacitor and that the surface becomes more homogeneous. The gradual addition of DHRE results in the replacement of water molecules by the organic molecules of DHRE on the MS surface. Consequently, the CPE value changes due to a reduction in the extent of metal dissolution. From the Nyquist diagrams, it is evident that the charge transfer resistance of MS in inhibited HCl solution significantly increases after the introduction of DHRE into the acidic solution.
